            "response_id": "resp_07ebb25758db48970069977abec8ec8197a1a1792b82fc3600",
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "This place is **Centralia, Pennsylvania**, and what’s special about it is that it’s a **near–ghost town created by a decades-long underground coal mine fire**.\n\n- **An underground fire has been burning beneath the town since 1962** (a coal-seam/mine fire). It spread through abandoned mine workings and has been extremely difficult to extinguish. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia_mine_fire))  \n- The fire caused **ground instability (subsidence), cracks, and vents that can emit heat/smoke and fumes**, making parts of the area unsafe and driving residents away. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia_mine_fire))  \n- Because of the hazards and failed/limited suppression efforts, the town was largely **condemned and bought out**; **Pennsylvania used eminent domain in 1992** and most residents relocated. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- Centralia’s population collapsed to **just a handful of residents (Wikipedia notes five residents as of the 2020 census)**, making it one of Pennsylvania’s least-populated municipalities. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- It also became famous for the now-closed **“Graffiti Highway”** (a damaged section of Route 61), which drew tourists before it was covered/blocked around **2020**. ([tnonline.com](https://www.tnonline.com/20250201/spotlight-centralia-gone-but-not-in-jeopardy-of-being-forgotten/))  \n\nIf you tell me what you mean by “this place” (e.g., share a photo or a map pin), I can confirm whether you meant Centralia itself or a nearby spot (like the vents/Big Mine Run area).",
